On Sep 18th, the SP500 was at 3357.01. Aftermarket indicates a 1.12% drop on Monday opening. For now, the SP500 has dropped 5.37% compared to August 27th. Before Tuesday, the major events driving SP500 includes: 1. Power steaps on Capitol Hill on Tuesday (possibly pushing the markets up if Powell addresses QE uncertainty) 2. Potential new stimulus bill 3. Tech giants law suits 4. Sept economic data 5. Big company earnings (NIKE on the 22nd, etc.) It is essentially impossible for SP to have a more than 12% move in either direction in this scenario. Unless September turns out to be a strong comeback in terms of Macro economic, is it hard to imagine that the SP will rally more than 2% in the following two days to achieve August's level. Thus, it is mostly likely for SP500 to end up down around 3-7% compared to Aug 28th.

Change in the S&P 500 is a highly random process, so I chose to model it with a random walk. I used daily returns over the past month to generate the distribution of changes for each step of the random walk to follow, and simulated the walk 100,000 times. This resulted in the following probabilities.

Using a similar approach to a TSLA forecasting question, we make use of option deltas to extract probabilities for each of the above buckets. The closest expiry to the date in question, Sept 22, is the Sept 18 calls/puts - however, without a strong prior I plan on taking the option deltas as is.

Cutoff numbers: 3087.05, 3367.69, 3648.33, 3928.97 Probabilities are derived from option deltas on Bloomberg, There doesn't appear to be any event in the next two weeks sparking a large jump, while investor sentiment that the market is currently overvalued could push it down more then 4%. Also we took into account that the SPX is negatively skewed, making large falls more likely than a normal.

We can try to back this out from options prices as well. We have the following buckets:

Similar to the Tesla question, we used the implied probabilities retrieved from the SPX options deltas to retrieve the market implied probability. This is reasonable given that the S&P 500 is very closely monitored by every investor and this market aggregate should cancel out noise from all the underlying models used by the market participants.

Base rate: I simulated the price of SP500 at time t as a Geometric Brownian motion. For mu the percentage drift and sigma the percentage volatility I used historical returns on different horizons: Jan 1st 19 or Jan 1st 20. For each case, I have then run 10,000 Monte Carlo simulations to get some probabilities for each range -> gives me 5%, 27%, 40%, 22%, 6% in the order of buckets of the question.
Sept 4 close = 3,426.96 which is only marginally less, 2.3%, than the 3,508.01 target. Surviving a near rout prior to a 3 day weekend, indicates to me that the market is incredibly solid near term.

I pretty much did the same thing (and will continue to do so) as I did with the TSLA question. I used SPX options data to back out the delta, which is the risk neutral probability under current implied volatility levels that the option will end up in the money. This is a rough heuristic after all (see risk neutral vs. real world probability difference here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_finance) and the delta is best for approximation near the strike. However, since I have no strong prior on this and SPX is reasonable volatile, I am basing my predictions on the market implied (risk-neutral) odds.
